article.description:
Anna DeForge had 21 points and seven rebounds, and the Phoenix Mercury beat the Indiana Fever 71-56 Saturday
night, despite missing top overall draft pick Diana Taurasi in the second half due to a bruised right thigh.
article.headline: Fever lose third straight
article.linkText: Taurasi hurt but Mercury roll past Fever
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Even without their top draft pick, the Phoenix
Mercury were too much for the Eastern Conference-leading Indiana
Fever.

Anna DeForge had 21 points, seven rebounds and five steals, and
Phoenix beat Indiana 71-56 Saturday night, despite missing No. 1
pick Diana Taurasi in the second half due to a bruised right thigh.

"It was a total team effort," Phoenix coach Carrie Graf said.
"We have been talking lately about using our last two performances
as a baseline for our future performance, and I believe we did that
tonight.

"For us to dig this win out during the second half against a
quality team like that was huge."

Taurasi, who ranks fourth in the league in scoring with an
18.1-point average, was injured late in the first half on a
collision and did not return. She finished with eight points, five
assists and two rebounds in 18 minutes. She has failed to reach
double figures only one other game this season, when she scored six
points on June 3 against Seattle.

Tamika Catchings had 15 points and eight rebounds for the Fever,
who lost their third straight and dropped a half-game behind
Connecticut and New York in the Eastern Conference after the Sun
beat San Antonio earlier Saturday. Indiana, which plays at
Sacramento on Sunday, lost its fifth straight road game.

DeForge shot 8-for-12 from the field, including 3-for-5 from
beyond the arc.

"We got the ball to the people who were slipping to the
basket," DeForge said. "We were shooting layups most of the
night. Defensively, we did a great job communicating --
communicating on switches, and denying their offense threat."

Taurasi, the player of the year for national champion
Connecticut earlier this year, entered the game as the top rookie
in the league in scoring, and ranked third overall in minutes per
game at 35.7.

Gwen Jackson scored 12 points in a reserve role for Phoenix.
Penny Taylor added 10, and newly acquired Jae Cross hit two
3-pointers subbing for Taurasi in the second half.

Phoenix scored eight straight points to break a 38-all tie with
16:04 remaining, and outscored Indiana 16-7 over the final 6:45.
The Mercury capitalized on Indiana's 38 percent shooting (20 of
53). The Fever rank last in the league in field goal percentage.
Indiana also had 19 turnovers, which led to 24 Phoenix points.

"We've been out for a week on the road and after a couple of
losses it gets you down a little bit," Indiana's Kristen Rasmussen
said.

Phoenix has won three straight since losing five in a row.
Indiana is 7-8 in its last 15 games. The Fever beat Phoenix on July
3 in Indianapolis 61-60.

DeForge hit consecutive 3-pointers in an 11-3 run, and had 12
points to lead Phoenix to a 34-32 halftime lead. Catchings had
seven points and five rebounds for Indiana, which made just three
of its first 12 shots.

"We need momentum; we need wins going into the break," said
DeForge.
